      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Dummy Bidding and Vendor Bids at Queensland Auctions
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Vendor bids are legal and transparent. Dummy bids are illegal and carry serious penalties. Here's what Queensland sellers need to understand about the rules before auction day.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Auctions sit at the sharper end of residential selling in Queensland. Done well, they concentrate genuine buyer demand into a single high-pressure moment and produce a result that represents the true market price on the day. Done poorly, they expose the seller to legal risk, buyer mistrust, and enforcement action from the Office of Fair Trading. A surprising amount of what separates the two comes down to two related but very different concepts: vendor bids and dummy bids. Sellers who confuse the two, or who take casual advice from friends and family about how to 'get the bidding moving', run real risk. This article walks through what each one actually is under Queensland law, why one is legal and the other is not, and how to run a clean, effective auction within the rules.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a vendor bid is</h2>
      <p>A vendor bid is a bid placed by the auctioneer on behalf of the seller during the auction. It is not a fake bid from a pretend buyer: it is an openly declared bid from the vendor, announced as such, and used to move the auction toward the reserve price or to start bidding when no genuine buyer is willing to open. In Queensland the rules governing vendor bids sit under the Property Occupations Act 2014 and the regulation that supports it. The core requirements are that the auctioneer must be permitted by the seller to make vendor bids, that the number of vendor bids must be disclosed or limited in the terms of the auction, and that every vendor bid must be clearly announced as a vendor bid at the moment it is made.</p>

      <p>In practice this means the auctioneer will say something like 'I have a vendor bid of $1,200,000' or 'a bid from the vendor at $1,250,000' before continuing to call. The disclosure is explicit and real-time. Genuine bidders hear exactly what is happening and can make their own decisions about whether to continue bidding with that information in front of them. Vendor bids are a tool of transparency, not a tool of deception, and that distinction is what makes them legal.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a dummy bid is, and why it is illegal</h2>
      <p>A dummy bid is a fake bid placed by someone connected to the seller: a friend, a family member, a business associate, or in rare cases the seller themselves, pretending to be a genuine buyer. The intent is to create the impression of competitive demand that does not actually exist, to push the bidding higher, or to prevent the property selling below a price the vendor is willing to accept. Dummy bidding is prohibited under Queensland law. It sits as a breach of the Property Occupations Act 2014 and of the agent's and auctioneer's professional obligations to conduct the auction honestly. It can also amount to misleading and deceptive conduct under Australian Consumer Law.</p>

      <p>The reason dummy bidding is treated so seriously is that it is a direct manipulation of price against genuine buyers. A buyer who pays an extra $50,000 because they were competing against a friend of the vendor pretending to bid has been cheated, in a very specific and legally cognisable sense. The information asymmetry is not a matter of opinion: the real buyer thinks they are in a market, and they are in a staged performance. The law protects the integrity of the auction process because the whole system relies on buyers trusting that the bids they are competing against are real.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The distinction that matters</h2>
      <p>The practical difference between a vendor bid and a dummy bid comes down to disclosure and who places it. A vendor bid is openly declared by the licensed auctioneer, announced as coming from the vendor, and permitted by the legal framework that governs the auction. A dummy bid is placed by a person pretending to be an independent buyer, without disclosure, with the intent to deceive the other bidders about the real state of demand for the property. Both might push the price to the same level. Only one is lawful.</p>

      <p>The other detail that matters is that vendor bids are typically used below the reserve price, not above it. Most reputable auctioneers will only exercise vendor bids while the bidding is still below what the vendor will accept: once the reserve is reached and the property is 'on the market', vendor bids are not needed and generally not used. This reinforces the transparency of the process. The vendor bid is a tool to help bidding reach the reserve, not a tool to extract an extra bid or two once genuine competition has already taken the price to a strong level.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why vendor bids exist and when they help</h2>
      <p>Auctions are theatrical by design. A cold start with no bids can stall momentum and make the property look unwanted, even when the underlying buyer interest is real. A vendor bid at a sensible opening level can give the auctioneer a platform to call from, signal to the crowd that the vendor is serious, and prompt genuine buyers off the fence. Used judiciously, typically one to two vendor bids at most, spaced early in the call, vendor bids can meaningfully improve a campaign's outcome.</p>

      <p>Vendor bids also serve a price-discovery function. They quietly signal to the room a price below which the vendor will not sell. Genuine buyers can decide whether to compete beyond that level, and if no one does, the property is passed in without drama and a post-auction negotiation begins. Compare this to a slow-moving cold start that produces no bids at all: the vendor bid gives the auctioneer something to call from, which is frequently more productive than a long silence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The penalties for dummy bidding</h2>
      <p>Dummy bidding carries significant consequences for everyone involved. The auctioneer and the listing agent can face fines and disciplinary action from the Office of Fair Trading, including conditions on or cancellation of their licence. The seller can be joined in regulatory action for directing or encouraging the conduct. Any buyer who can show they paid more than they would have because of the dummy bid may bring a civil claim for damages or, in more serious cases, seek to have the sale set aside. The reputational fallout for agents involved in dummy bidding cases is usually severe and long-lasting in the local market.</p>

      <p>Beyond the formal penalties, dummy bidding undermines the seller's own interests. Buyers and buyers' agents in the inner Brisbane market are well-networked and actively share information about campaigns that feel staged. A campaign that gets a reputation for dummy bidding loses the genuine buyers the seller was trying to attract, and the next time the property comes back to market, it carries baggage.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should not do</h2>
      <p>The clearest advice for Queensland sellers is to keep a hard line between their legitimate role and anything that might amount to dummy bidding. Do not ask friends, family members, or colleagues to attend the auction and place bids on your behalf. Do not attend yourself and bid anonymously on your own property through an alias or a family member's paddle. Do not encourage or pressure the auctioneer to make more vendor bids than were agreed in the pre-auction meeting, and do not ask them to place vendor bids above the reserve to extract a higher price. Do not collude with another bidder to withdraw in exchange for a side benefit. Any of these actions moves the auction from a legally managed vendor-bid strategy into unlawful territory.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers can legitimately do</h2>
      <p>There is plenty a vendor can do within the rules to run a strong auction. The pre-auction briefing is where most of the meaningful decisions are made: agreeing the reserve with the agent, agreeing the maximum number of vendor bids and the price points at which they will be used, agreeing a signal (an eye-contact cue or a nod) by which the agent can communicate with you during the call. During the auction itself you can consult with the agent between calls, you can vary the reserve, you can instruct the agent to accept or decline an offer after a pass-in. All of these are legitimate, and all of them are far more effective at producing a strong result than any form of dummy bidding.</p>

      <p>The trust between vendor, listing agent, and auctioneer is the scaffolding of a good auction. A vendor who has chosen a credible agent and auctioneer, agreed a clear pre-auction plan, and then trusts them to execute it within the rules will almost always produce a better outcome than a vendor who tries to manipulate the bidding from the sidelines.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The enforcement environment is tightening</h2>
      <p>The Office of Fair Trading in Queensland has increased its focus on auction conduct in recent years, including spot attendance at auctions and follow-up reviews of campaigns where buyers have complained. Agents have had licences suspended or cancelled for dummy bidding practices, and some high-profile cases have ended with sales being unwound and damages paid. The upside for honest vendors is that a clean auction process now has a genuine market premium: buyers who trust the process are more willing to bid confidently, which is precisely what a seller wants.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Run a clean auction. Agree the reserve and the vendor bid strategy in writing before the day. Make sure your auctioneer is licensed, experienced, and clear on the announcement rules. Communicate with them through the signals you have agreed, not through third parties in the crowd. Do not invite friends or family to bid on your behalf under any circumstance, no matter how informally it is suggested. If the bidding falls short of the reserve and the property is passed in, deal with that honestly through the post-auction negotiation, not by trying to engineer a higher price through fake competition.</p>

      <p>The sellers who consistently do well at auction in Brisbane's inner east are the ones who prepare their property carefully, price it realistically, and trust the process. The rules around vendor bids and dummy bidding exist to protect the integrity of that process, and in practice they are also the framework that produces the best outcome for a seller who plays it straight.</p>

